Description. Body green, forewings usually more or less darkened, especially in apical part, in males darker than in females (
Figs. 2–7
). In darkest males, forewings almost black with widely lightened costal margin (
Fig. 2
). In light-coloured specimens forewings entirely translucent with green veins (
Figs. 4, 7
). Proportion of specimens with dark forewings varies greatly between different localities.

Pygofer processes almost straight, with tips slightly bent forward (Figs. 
15, 25–26
). Penis in side view comparatively short and broad (Figs. 
16, 27–29
). Style tips pointed and somewhat bent inwards (Figs. 
17, 30–33
). 
2
nd valvulae of ovipositor with 
3–5
preapical teeth (Figs. 
34–36
).

Nymph either entirely black (

Fig. 
8

) or bright green (

Fig. 
9

); nymphs with intermediate coloration (as in adult specimens, 

Figs. 
3, 6

) were not found.

Calling signal. Signal consists of repeated phrases following one after another without gaps (
Figs. 37–50
). Each phrase begins with trill sounding like monotonous buzz, followed by succession of pulses; pulses at end of succession sometimes merge together. Durations of each part as well as of whole phrase vary greatly. Males usually sing unceasingly for several minutes.
